{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcwJev72F6Kv6vWbhnHG9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The `--dry-run` flag (short form `-n`) makes rsync perform a **trial run without making any actual changes**. It goes through the entire transfer process and reports exactly what *would* happen, but doesn't create, modify, delete, or copy any files.\n\nIt's most useful for previewing a command before running it for real — especially when using potentially destructive options like `--delete`.\n\n**Example:**\n```bash\nrsync -av --delete --dry-run source/ destination/\n```\nThis shows which files would be copied and which would be deleted, letting you verify the behavior is what you expect before removing `--dry-run` to run it for real.\n\n**Key points:**\n- Combine with `-v` (verbose) to see the list of affected files — `--dry-run` alone is less useful without it.\n- The output should closely match the real run, though byte counts in the summary are estimates since no data is actually transferred.\n- It's read-only safe: nothing on the destination is touched.\n\nA common workflow is to run with `--dry-run` first, eyeball the output, then re-run the identical command without the flag."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5443,"cache_read_input_tokens":16984,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5443},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fd88e00b-abd2-43b6-8daf-b0081d9c22a7","uuid":"2ab376f7-4a4d-46ad-be00-f40686d5738c","request_id":"req_011CcwJeuLtQjTxzk2UCHCrp"}
